## 9. Phase E – Restore a Single Tablespace

## Preferred Method: Restore to Staging Database

This is the safest approach because it avoids direct risk to the UAT source database.

---

### 9.1 Create staging database

```sh
db2 create db $STAGING_DB using codeset UTF-8 territory US
```

Prepare log/archive paths:

```sh
mkdir -p $ARCHIVE_BASE/$STAGING_DB/active
mkdir -p $ARCHIVE_BASE/$STAGING_DB/archive
```

Configure logging:

```sh
db2 update db cfg for $STAGING_DB using LOGARCHMETH1 DISK:$ARCHIVE_BASE/$STAGING_DB/archive
db2 update db cfg for $STAGING_DB using NEWLOGPATH $ARCHIVE_BASE/$STAGING_DB/active
db2 update db cfg for $STAGING_DB using TRACKMOD YES
```

Clear backup pending on staging DB:

```sh
db2 backup database $STAGING_DB to $BACKUP_BASE/full/tgt1 compress
```

**Paste screenshot reference:**  
`[SCREENSHOT-14: Staging DB prepared]`

---

### 9.2 Start redirected restore of the single tablespace

> Important: clause order matters. In DB2, keep the syntax in the correct order: **FROM / TAKEN AT / INTO / REDIRECT**.

Example:

```sh
db2 "restore db $DB_NAME tablespace ($TS_NAME) \
from $BACKUP_BASE/full/tgt1,$BACKUP_BASE/full/tgt2 \
taken at <BACKUP_TIMESTAMP_TEST> \
into $STAGING_DB redirect"
```

If the backup image spans only one path, reduce the `from` clause accordingly.

**Paste screenshot reference:**  
`[SCREENSHOT-15: Redirected tablespace restore started]`

---

### 9.3 Set containers for the restored tablespace in staging

First identify the tablespace ID in the restore context if needed.

Example explicit container mapping:

```sh
mkdir -p $DATA_BASE/$STAGING_DB/$TS_NAME

db2 "set tablespace containers for <TS_ID> using (file '$DATA_BASE/$STAGING_DB/$TS_NAME/${TS_NAME}.cont' 200000)"
```

If automatic storage is used end-to-end, container management may differ. In that case verify whether explicit container mapping is still required for the redirected restore in your layout.

**Paste screenshot reference:**  
`[SCREENSHOT-16: Container mapping for restored tablespace]`

---

### 9.4 Continue the restore

```sh
db2 "restore db $STAGING_DB continue"
```

**Paste screenshot reference:**  
`[SCREENSHOT-17: Restore continued successfully]`

---

### 9.5 Roll forward the staging DB / restored tablespace

If the scenario is row recovery after a delete, roll forward to PIT:

```sh
db2 "rollforward db $STAGING_DB to <PIT_TIMESTAMP> using local time and stop"
```

If the scenario is object recovery from the backup image only and no PIT is needed, test whether end-of-logs is sufficient:

```sh
db2 "rollforward db $STAGING_DB to end of logs and stop"
```

Check status:

```sh
db2 rollforward db $STAGING_DB query status
```

**Paste screenshot reference:**  
`[SCREENSHOT-18: Rollforward completed]`

---

### 9.6 Validate recovered objects/data in staging

```sh
db2 connect to $STAGING_DB

db2 "select tabschema, tabname, tbspace from syscat.tables where tabschema='RCVLAB' order by tabname"
db2 "select * from RCVLAB.T_RESTORE_A order by ID"
db2 "select * from RCVLAB.T_RESTORE_B order by ID"
```

